11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41950"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of mild dysuria with associated lower abdominal pain. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include amlodipine and metformin, and he was recently started on a new diabetes medication. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild suprapubic tenderness. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dapagliflozin","Metformin","Gliclazide","Tirzepatide","Sitagliptin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a urinary tract infection, including dysuria, lower abdominal pain, and mild fever. The temporal relationship with starting a new diabetes medication is significant. Among the medications listed, one class is particularly associated with an increased risk of genitourinary infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is a sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT-2) inhibitor that works by blocking glucose reabsorption in the proximal tubules of the kidney, leading to increased urinary glucose excretion. This glycosuria creates a favourable environment for bacterial and fungal growth, resulting in an increased incidence of urinary tract infections and genital mycotic infections. Studies have consistently shown this association across all SGLT-2 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is a biguanide that primarily works by decreasing hepatic glucose production and increasing insulin sensitivity. It is not associated with an increased risk of urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGliclazide\u003C/strong\u003E is a sulfonylurea that stimulates insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells. While it can cause hypoglycaemia and weight gain, it is not associated with urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETirzepatide\u003C/strong\u003E is a dual glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide (GIP) and glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptor agonist. Common side effects include gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea and diarrhoea, but it is not associated with an increased risk of urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESitagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E is a dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-4) inhibitor that increases incretin levels, leading to increased insulin secretion and decreased glucagon secretion. It is generally well-tolerated and not associated with urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism underlying the increased infection risk with SGLT-2 inhibitors relates to the persistent glycosuria they cause. The elevated glucose concentration in urine provides an ideal growth medium for pathogens. Patients starting SGLT-2 inhibitors should be counselled about maintaining good genital hygiene and recognising symptoms of genitourinary infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dapagliflozin is an oral hypoglycaemic agent of the SGLT-2 inhibitor class that is associated with an increased frequency of urinary tract infections.","SGLT-2 inhibitors increase urinary glucose excretion, creating a favourable environment for bacterial growth in the urinary tract.","Patients starting SGLT-2 inhibitors should be counselled about the increased risk of genitourinary infections."],"references":["Bailey CJ, Gross JL, Pieters A, Bastien A, List JF. Effect of dapagliflozin in patients with type 2 diabetes who have inadequate glycaemic control with metformin: a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial. Lancet 2010;375:2223-33.","Ferrannini E, Ramos SJ, Salsali A, Tang W, List JF. Dapagliflozin monotherapy in type 2 diabetic patients with inadequate glycemic control by diet and exercise: a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, phase 3 trial. Diabetes Care 2010;33:2217-24"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-07T09:08:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-07T09:10:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi